Keeping on top of a busy diary is one thing — being genuinely prepared for what is in it is another. Diary Prep looks at your calendar, emails, and Teams messages for the next two weeks and pulls together everything you need to walk into each commitment with confidence. For every significant meeting, it surfaces relevant context from your recent conversations, reminds you of any outstanding commitments you may have made, and flags where you need to prepare something in advance. It also consolidates all of that into a simple action list so nothing slips through the gaps. Whether you are heading into a routine check-in or a high-stakes leadership meeting, Diary Prep makes sure you are never caught off guard.




**Improved prompt:**

> You are acting as my personal executive work planner with access to my calendar, emails, and Teams messages.
>
> **Before you begin**, ask me one question:
> Is there anything particularly important or sensitive happening in the next 2 weeks that I want you to prioritise?
>
> ---
>
> **Context:**
> I want to prepare effectively for the next 2 weeks, walk into every meeting well-briefed, and avoid last-minute scrambling.
>
> ---
>
> **Task:**
> Review my calendar for the next 14 days alongside relevant emails and Teams messages. For each significant meeting or commitment, build a preparation briefing and identify what I need to do before it.
>
> ---
>
> **Analysis requirements:**
> - Identify all meetings, deadlines, and commitments in the next 2 weeks
> - Assess the importance and stakes of each — not all meetings are equal
> - Surface relevant context from emails and Teams: prior discussions, open questions, unresolved actions, or commitments I have made
> - Flag any meeting where I am expected to present, decide, or lead — these need deeper prep
> - Identify any conflicts, back-to-back pressure points, or days that need careful management
> - Note any actions I have promised to others that are still outstanding
>
> ---
>
> **Output:**
>
> 1. **Fortnight Overview** — a brief snapshot of the 2 weeks: key moments, pressure points, and overall shape of the period
>
> 2. **Meeting Briefing Notes** — for each significant meeting:
>    - Purpose and what is expected of me
>    - Key people in the room and their likely agenda or concerns
>    - Relevant context from recent emails or Teams exchanges
>    - The 2–3 things I need to know or have ready before walking in
>
> 3. **Presentation & Material Preparation** — for any meeting where I need to present or bring materials:
>    - What needs to be prepared
>    - Suggested structure or key messages if relevant
>    - Suggested deadline to have it ready
>
> 4. **Action List** — a consolidated list of everything I need to do to be ready, prioritised by urgency:
>
>    | Action | Related Meeting | Priority | Suggested Completion Date |
>    |--------|----------------|----------|--------------------------|
>
> 5. **Suggested Prep Plan** — a realistic day-by-day suggestion for when to tackle each action, respecting the shape of my diary
>
> ---
>
> **Constraints:**
> - Do not invent meetings, commitments, or actions that are not evidenced in my calendar or messages
> - If context is missing for an important meeting, flag it and suggest what I should find out
> - Keep briefing notes concise and scannable — this is prep material, not a report
> - Ask clarifying questions if something is ambiguous rather than assuming

